<section xml:id="sec-6-3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Rational Exponents</title>

<introduction><title>Overview</title>
<p>In this Lesson we extend the study of rational exponents to powers of the form <m>a^{m/n}</m>. We simplify expressions using the laws of exponents, solve equations, and look at models that use power functions with rational exponents.</p>
    
<p>Begin class by reviewing the types of exponents we have already studied, and show how the defintion of rational exponents makes sense. You may want to practice using the laws of exponents, but do not make the examples unreasonably complicated, or the discussion may devolve into a lesson on adding fractions. It is also useful to solve a few equations that involve rational exponents.</p></introduction>

<activity xml:id="act-6-3-1"><title>Kepler's Law</title>

<introduction><p>Kepler's law gives a relation between the period <m>p</m> of a planet's revolution and its average distance <m>a</m> from the sun:
  <me>p^2=Ka^3</me>
where <m>K=1.243 \times 10^{-6}</m>, <m>p</m> is in millions of miles, and <m>a</m> is in years.</p></introduction>

